ich our ever-evolving sense of self unfolds. His essays weave together memoir, history, and political thinking to explore meanings and experiences of home: home as place, community, bodies, identity, and activism. Here readers will find an intersectional framework for understanding how we actually live with the daily hydraulics of oppression, power, and resistance. At the root of Clare's exploration of environmental destruction and capitalism, sexuality and institutional violence, gender and the body politic, is a call for social justice movements that are truly accessible to everyone. With heart and hammer, Exile and Pride pries open a window onto a world where our whole selves, in all their complexity, can be realized, loved, and embraced.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCerebral palsiedzUnited StatesvBiography. 0aGender identity. 0aPolitical activistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aSexual minorities with disabilitieszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aTransgender peoplezUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen political activistszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh1 aMorales, Aurora Levins, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpade, Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorales, Aurora Levins1 aSpade, Dean08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822374879zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822374879423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822374879.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles